 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.11","title":"Continuously monitor mailbox health and launch preemptive recovery before user-visible failure","description":"Add proactive runtime drift and suspect-state detection so archive-ahead, empty-DB, deleted-owner, and stale-health conditions trigger safe background recovery before ordinary users notice.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:20:24.522372846Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:25:57.299656806Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:25:57.299370109Z","close_reason":"Implemented in durability program commits","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.11","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:20:24.522372846Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.11","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.10","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:20:25.330229300Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.11","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:20:24.917266211Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.11","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:20:25.115779743Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1329,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.11","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead makes the durability system proactive instead of merely reactive. It should define periodic health sampling, freshness windows, suspicion thresholds, and when the supervisor is allowed to start a quiet background rebuild before any user-facing command observes a broken mailbox.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:20:25Z"}]}
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","title":"Preserve read-your-writes semantics for accepted writes during degraded recovery","description":"Specify and implement how accepted deferred or archive-first writes remain visible to the originating user, API surface, and later readers while SQLite is degraded or rebuilding, without lying about durability state.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:26:32.177227214Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:34:51.406047541Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:34:51.405829122Z","close_reason":"Implemented","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:26:32.177227214Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.19","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:59:25.220694896Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:26:32.670388900Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:26:32.907011275Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:26:33.155848299Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1345,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead exists for trust. If the system accepts a write during recovery, users should not see that action vanish from subsequent reads just because SQLite is rebuilding. The plan should define pending-write overlays, durability labels, reconciliation rules, and exactly when a surface may say 'accepted but still replaying' versus showing the fully materialized result.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:26:34Z"}]}
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.13","title":"Define latency, IO, and cancellation budgets for background or preemptive recovery","description":"Specify how proactive and background rebuild work is rate-limited, deprioritized, paused, or canceled so self-healing does not degrade foreground reads, writes, or operator interactions.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:28:25.718379894Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:26:00.724345986Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:26:00.724124752Z","close_reason":"Implemented in durability program commits","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.13","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:28:25.718379894Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.13","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.11","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:28:26.189323554Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1347,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.13","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead is about invisible quality. Background recovery should help users, not steal latency from them. The plan should define CPU and IO budgets, pause or cancel rules under foreground pressure, how accepted writes are prioritized relative to rebuild work, and what telemetry proves the system is healing quietly instead of becoming the new source of slowness.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:29:35Z"}]}
-{"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","title":"Define compensation and follow-up when accepted deferred writes later fail replay","description":"Specify how overlays, archive truth, user-visible status, and operator follow-up are reconciled if a write accepted during degradation cannot later be replayed cleanly into the rebuilt index.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:35.660209243Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:34:51.397751327Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:34:51.397547896Z","close_reason":"Implemented","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:35.660209243Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:36.561772204Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.19","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:59:34.134990636Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:36.105359121Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:36.334106766Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1350,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead closes the last major trust gap in deferred writes. If the system says yes first and replay fails later, the plan must define what the user sees next, what remains authoritative, what gets compensated or retried, and how operators are told exactly what happened without pretending the write fully succeeded.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:37Z"}]}
+{"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","title":"Define compensation and follow-up when accepted deferred writes later fail replay","description":"Specify how overlays, archive truth, user-visible status, and operator follow-up are reconciled if a write accepted during degradation cannot later be replayed cleanly into the rebuilt index.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:35.660209243Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:43:03.768358488Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:43:03.768138056Z","close_reason":"Implemented in durability program commits","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:35.660209243Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.12","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:36.561772204Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.19","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:59:34.134990636Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.8","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:36.105359121Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.9","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:36.334106766Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1350,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.14","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead closes the last major trust gap in deferred writes. If the system says yes first and replay fails later, the plan must define what the user sees next, what remains authoritative, what gets compensated or retried, and how operators are told exactly what happened without pretending the write fully succeeded.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:37Z"}]}
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.15","title":"Version recovery receipts, forensic manifests, and verification artifacts with compatibility rules","description":"Define schema versions, backward-read policy, upgrade behavior, golden compatibility fixtures, structured logging, and shell E2E replay or upgrade coverage for recovery receipts, forensic bundle manifests, dry-run plan fingerprints, and durability verification artifacts.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:33:45.844890773Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.184877966Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.184683903Z","close_reason":"Implemented","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.15","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:33:45.844890773Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.15","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:33:46.304221231Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.15","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:33:46.493598584Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1353,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.15","author":"ubuntu","text":"The plan now depends on many machine-readable artifacts: receipts, manifests, plan fingerprints, canary logs, and replay bundles. This bead ensures they have an explicit versioning and compatibility story so upgrades do not strand old evidence, break replay tools, or make CI artifacts unreadable across releases.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:33:47Z"},{"id":1354,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.15","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead must explicitly cover mixed-version durability evidence. Scope should include table-driven unit tests for schema readers and writers, golden fixtures for receipts and bundle manifests, shell E2E scripts that replay or upgrade old artifacts through new binaries, and structured logs that always report artifact version, reader behavior, upgrade decision, and rerun hints.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:39:27Z"}]}
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.16","title":"Define crash-safe recovery checkpoints, interrupted-attempt resume rules, and orphan candidate cleanup","description":"Specify what metadata and phase checkpoints the mailbox supervisor must persist so abrupt process death, kill -9, machine restart, or upgrade interruption can resume or safely roll back recovery without split-brain promotion, leaked candidates, or lost deferred writes. Include startup resume policy, orphan-candidate quarantine rules, receipt semantics, and explicit unit plus chaos verification expectations.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:41:49.241434484Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.176026673Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.175787105Z","close_reason":"Implemented","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.16","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:41:49.241434484Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.16","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:44:20.073274824Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.16","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.10","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:44:31.435031410Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.16","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.5","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:44:25.188880262Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.16","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:44:28.397169910Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1355,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.16","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead closes the last major correctness gap in the durability plan: abrupt death in the middle of recovery. The system should persist enough phase information to make the next startup classify an interrupted attempt as resumable, rollback-only, or quarantine-only; it must never dual-promote, leak a half-built candidate into service, or forget accepted deferred writes. Scope should explicitly include table-driven unit tests for every phase transition, kill-point-aware chaos coverage, and structured logs that name the interrupted phase, resume decision, surviving artifacts, and exact rerun path.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:45:45Z"}]}
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.17","title":"Define safety mode and authority rules when the archive source of truth is unreadable or inconsistent","description":"Specify how the mailbox supervisor behaves when the Git archive itself is unreadable, partially corrupted, or inconsistent with persisted receipts. The system must avoid destructive auto-recovery, preserve both archive and SQLite evidence, choose the safest bounded read behavior, escalate only to the right audience, and remain explicit about what is and is not authoritative. Include unit-test matrices, shell E2E scenarios, and structured logging requirements for archive-damaged incidents.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:48:16.696507482Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.229047706Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.228838094Z","close_reason":"Implemented","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.17","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:48:16.696507482Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.17","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:49:45.862334569Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.17","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:49:46.044987282Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.17","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:50:46.159320376Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.17","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:50:16.091365423Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1358,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.17","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead covers the uncomfortable but crucial case where the archive can no longer be treated as clean truth. The plan should force a safety-hold mode that preserves both sides as evidence, forbids destructive normalization or recovery steps, makes bounded-read behavior explicit, and verifies the exact operator copy and escalation thresholds with unit matrices plus shell E2E scenarios. The goal is to avoid turning a source-of-truth problem into permanent data loss through overconfident automation.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:54:33Z"}]}
@@ -1630,7 +1630,7 @@
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","title":"Integrate forensic capture into startup, doctor, and supervisor recovery paths","description":"Wire forensic capture into every recovery entrypoint that can mutate mailbox state.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:14.701784415Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:38.686728881Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:26:32.000746717Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:14.701784415Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:15.364212905Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:15.630802248Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:38.685578446Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1296,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead enforces one evidence standard across:\n- startup auto-recovery\n- doctor repair/reconstruct\n- background supervisor recovery\n\nNo mutating recovery path should remain that can skip bundle capture accidentally.\n","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:15Z"}]}
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.5","title":"Add operator helpers that point directly at forensic bundles","description":"Make startup, doctor, and operator surfaces reference bundle paths and terse summaries instead of raw evidence dumps.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:15.856550542Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:16.548345479Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.5","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:15.856550542Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.5","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:16.547181568Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1297,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.5","author":"ubuntu","text":"The forensic bundle only helps if operators can find it quickly.\n\nThis bead should make bundle discovery easy enough that engineers do not need to grep the filesystem manually after every incident.\n","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:07:16Z"}]}
 {"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.6","title":"Add golden tests for forensic bundle schema, redaction, and replay handoff","description":"Lock down forensic bundle manifest shape, artifact completeness, sensitive-field redaction, and replay readiness with golden fixtures and negative tests.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:24:07.547700462Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.294492145Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T01:35:05.294301689Z","close_reason":"Implemented","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.6","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.1.15","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:33:46.975471105Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.6","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:24:07.547700462Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.6","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:24:07.969627264Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.6","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:24:08.171990417Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.6","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.7","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:38.915059485Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1342,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.6","author":"ubuntu","text":"The bundle format needs its own stability contract. Without schema and redaction goldens, later recovery changes can silently make bundles harder to trust, harder to replay, or too risky to share.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:24:08Z"}]}
-{"id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.7","title":"Constrain forensic bundle permissions, sharing rules, and optional encrypted export","description":"Define filesystem permissions, safe local access defaults, and whether or how forensic bundles may be further redacted or encrypted before off-box sharing or CI artifact upload.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:38.041396201Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:39.328848902Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.7","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:38.041396201Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.7","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:38.488626465Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1351,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.3.7","author":"ubuntu","text":"Forensic bundles are useful only if they are both diagnosable and safe to handle. This bead should define default file permissions, local access expectations, when encrypted export is required, and how CI or release workflows avoid turning incident artifacts into a new secrecy problem.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:39Z"}]}
