:26:36.569360892Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.6.5.2","depends_on_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.6.5.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:32:40.768480371Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":1340,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.6.5.2","author":"ubuntu","text":"This bead closes the loop from one-time verification to continuous assurance. The canaries should run only against isolated storage roots, emit the same structured artifacts as the main durability lanes, and alert on regressions before production users notice anything.","created_at":"2026-04-02T20:21:54Z"},{"id":1372,"issue_id":"br-97gc6.5.2.6.5.2","author":"ubuntu","text":"Synthetic canaries should reuse the same incident-fixture vocabulary and artifact schema as the main E2E lane rather than inventing a second parallel notion of incidents. That keeps continuous assurance aligned with the real regression corpus and makes canary failures directly comparable to developer-run durability scenarios.","created_at":"2026-04-02T21:16:15Z"}]}
